<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Condemns Child Sexual Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today criticized media and certain section of society for
promoting moral decadence among Zimbabwean youth which has
triggered an increase in sexual abuse of children in the past few
months.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates attending the commemoration of the Day of
the African Child in Harare, Mugabe expressed shock at reports of
rape, most of which involve children which he said,
demonstrated that morality was no longer a virtue in society.
</P>
<P>
He said, "When a father rapes his own two or three year-old
girl child, one begins to wonder what is becoming of our
society."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has lately witnessed an upsurge in the number of rape
cases, some involving six months old infants.
</P>
<P>
The upsurge has resulted in calls for stiffer penalties for
perpetrators, with some women's groups advocating the castration
of convicted rapists.
</P>
<P>
"We need to conscientize society and make it feel that it has
a duty to ensure that no child is abused," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
This year's Day of the African Child embraced 150 child
parliamentarians who debated key issues affecting Zimbabwean
children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
