<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jospin Calls on Socialists Not to Attack Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister and First
Secretary of the Socialist Party Lionel Jospin today appealed to
the adherents of his leftist movement not to attack his government
over such issues as the European single currency and closure of
the Renault Vilvoorde auto plant.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the national conference of the Socialist Party,
Jospin said that he wanted to establish "rules of the game"
between the government and the party.
</P>
<P>
Jospin has been severely criticized by some radical Socialists
for ratifying the Stability Pact of the European Union at the
Amsterdam summit early last month, which imposed strict
restriction on budget spending upon future members of the single
currency.
</P>
<P>
He was also chastised for failing to stop the Renault automaker
from closing its Vilvoorde auto plant in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Jospin reminded the party members that the rightist parties of
France had "hardened" their position after their defeat in the
legislative elections, and that they were closing in with the
extreme right.
</P>
<P>
One month after coming to power, the prime minister admitted
that it was very difficult to make the two ends of his electoral
promises and France's engagement for the European monetary union
meet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
