<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting in Cambodia Kills at Least Five People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Sporadic fighting here between
forces loyal to the country's co-prime ministers left at least
five people killed and 50 others injured.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges of fire erupted in a camp about 20 kilometers
from the capital, when troops loyal to Second Prime Minister Hun
Sen tried to confiscate weapons of those supporting First Prime
Minister Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
At about 3 p.m., some 1,000 troops loyal to Hun Sen besieged a
camp of those loyal to the prince at about eight kilometers west
of the capital. Both sides used rocket launchers and mortars in
their hours of fighting, leaving a number of civilian and military
casualties.
</P>
<P>
Heavy shelling was also reported near a down town hospital in
the afternoon. At least five shells exploded in residential
quarters.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary statistics, at least five people were
killed and more than 50 others injured in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Local hospitals have said they would have no ability to receive
more wounded people, most of whom are civilians.
</P>
<P>
In the tense situation caused by the fighting, the capital's
only international airport, banks and shops were closed.
</P>
<P>
The Phnom Penh city government announced that an indefinite
curfew was imposed in the city.
</P>
<P>
An advisor to Ranariddh today accused Hun Sen of attempting a
coup d'etat, while Hun Sen charged his co-premier with treachery
and preparing for war.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, now reportedly in Vietnam, made a statement on the
state television, said he would take all necessary measures to
protect the interests of the country and the people.
</P>
<P>
The prince and his top advisers were reportedly out of the
country. The radio loyal to the prince stopped broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said the troops loyal to the prince were likely to
be bombarded again on Sunday, until they accept the conditions set
by those supporting Hun Sen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
