<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Clashes Continue in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The violent clashes between
Palestinian rioters and Israeli soldiers continued in Hebron
today, during which at least two Palestinians were injured.
</P>
<P>
The scale of today's clashes was relatively lower compared
with the past days since the violence began last Saturday. Dozens
of Palestinian youths threw stones and firebombs at Israeli
soldiers who responded with rubber bullets and tear gas,
injuring one Palestinian protester.
</P>
<P>
Today's clashes lasted only for several hours this morning,
and the situation reportedly stabilized in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
What was new was that a group of Jewish settlers living in
Hebron joined for the first time in the confrontation by
throwing stones and rubbish at the Palestinians. A Palestinian
woman passerby was lightly injured. The settlers also shouted
the offensive anti-Islamic slogan "Mohammed (the Islamic prophet)
is a pig."
</P>
<P>
Since Israeli troops redeployed from 80 percent of Hebron
under the agreement signed in January, about 450 Jewish settlers
remained living on the other 20 percent of the city, which was
heavily guarded by Israeli soldiers. Hebron has long been the
showcase of the Israeli-Palestinian confrontations.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of violence in the volatile city was sparked
last Saturday by a leaflet depicting Mohammed as a pig writing
the holy Koran. The leaflets were pasted in the city's
storefronts by a rightist Jewish woman from Jerusalem, who has
been charged with offending religious sensibilities at the
Jerusalem District Court.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of Muslims demonstrated in Nazareth of
norhtern Israel this afternoon to protest the blasphemous act
against Islam. The demonstration was organized by the Islamic
Movement to protest the Hebron leaflets.
</P>
<P>
A large number of Israeli police were put on high alert
against possible outbreak of violence, but the demonstration
passed quietly.
</P>
<P>
The latest wave of violence erupted against the backdrop of
the prolonged deadlock of Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. The
peace process has been frozen since March when Israel began
building the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) is demanding an halt
to the settlement activities as a precondition for resuming the
talks, while the Israeli government insists on the PNA's promise
to resume security cooperation with Israel and to launch a
long-term crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent mediation efforts by the United Sates and
Egypt, the deadlock continued due to the wide gap between the
two sides, leading to fears about widespread escalation of
violence in the Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
