<HEADLINE> Minister: Jordan Sides With Arabs on Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Minister of Trade, Industry
and Supply Hani Moulki said today that his country might retrack
its former decision to attend the Doha economic conference slated
for November.
</P>
<P>
This came in statements by the Jordanian minister following his
meeting here this afternoon with Egyptian Minister of Economy and
International Cooperation Nawal Tatawi.
</P>
<P>
"My country has previously declared its approval to take part
in the conference but it eventually sides with the Arab stance,"
said Moulki.
</P>
<P>
Discouraged by the lack of a breakthrough in the deadlocked
peace process, several Arab countries have decided to boycott the
fourth Middle East and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference
which Israel will participate. Egypt has yet to announce its own
decision.
</P>
<P>
Amman and Cairo, the hosts to the previous two MENA conferences
and the only two Arab countries to have made peace with Israel,
have played important mediating roles in the Mideast peace
process, which has sunk into deep crisis.
</P>
<P>
Switching to Arab economic integration, Moulki referred to
the call of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and King Hussein of
Jordan for setting up an Arab common market that can face up to
world economic pressures.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt was the first to call for setting up an Arab free trade
zone as a nucleus of the Arab common market," he said. "Jordan
believes that it is the right way so that the Arab area would be
of economic importance in the new economic world," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ten Jordanian ministers arrived here today for the 14th
Egyptian-Jordanian Higher Committee meetings set to start this
evening under the co-chairmanship of Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri and his Jordanian counterpart Abdul-Salam Majali.
</P>
<P>
Tatawi, in her turn, underlined that present world political
and economic developments and changes require further cooperation
and integration among all Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The preparatory committee of the Egyptian-Jordanian Higher
Committee has adopted recommendations that might boost
distinguished relations between the two countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
Foremost among those recommendations is working to increase the
volume of trade exchange between the two countries, she added.
</P>
<P>
Two agreements on electrical linkage and joint technical
cooperation in the field of livestock will be signed, she said.
</P>
<P>
Altogether six agreements and protocols of cooperation between
Egypt and Jordan in economic and cultural fields will be signed
during the two-day committee meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
