<HEADLINE> Turkmenia Protests Russia-Azerbaijan Oil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Turkmen Foreign Ministry today
lodged a "strong protest" against signing of a Russian-Azerbaijani
agreement on the joint development of the Kyapaz oil field in the
Caspina Sea, which the ministry states belongs to Turkmenia.
</P>
<P>
The Russia-Azerbaijani agreement was signed Friday during the
visit of Azerbaijani President Geidar Aliyev to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The Turkmen side demanded that "the agreement be annulled to
avoid the consequences for which Turkmenistan will not bear any
responsibility."
</P>
<P>
The ministry in a statement said that international legal order
should be restored in the Caspian Sea area, taking into account
the new political realities and the need to ensure civilized use
of its resources in the interests of all littoral states.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenia has repeatedly asked Azerbaijan to begin constructive
dialogue and refrain from any specific actions before an agreement
is reached.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, we cannot but be surprised, to say the least,
by the decision adopted by Russia and Azerbaijan with regard to
the oil field, for Turkmenistan's rights to this deposit are
obvious and cannot be a matter of ambiguous interpretation," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Russian Ambassador Vadim Cherepov was
summoned to the Turkmen Foreign Ministry earlier today to hear its
"strong protest." Enitem

