<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican President on Democracy in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- President Joachim Chissano
of Mozambique today warned Africans against those who tried to
impose their own brands of democracy on the African countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that no society is in a position to teach others
how they should implement their own democratic processes,
although it is equally important that they should learn from each
other.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican president made the remarks when opening a
three-day international conference on democracy and development
in the town of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
"Democratization is a process, sometimes a very long process
and circumstances vary from country to country," Chissano said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that democracy is a process and that it starts
from a point of less democracy in the direction of more
democracy, adding that countries are better advised not to jump
overnight from one stage of democracy to the other without being
ready for that jump.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of peace for the African continent,
the Mozambican president said that development and democracy
should only occur in a peaceful environment and within peaceful
countries where trust and confidence are built through dialogue
amongst its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
President Chissano arrived in the town of Zanzibar on Friday
purposely for the opening ceremony of the conference, which is
attended by members of parliament from some African countries
and that from Ireland, Sweden and Denmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
