<HEADLINE> Angolan Ruling Party's National Congress Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Popular Movement for the
Liberation of Angola (MPLA) today called on the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to move its
headquarters to the capital as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued at the end of its second national
congress, the MPLA also urged an earliest meeting between Angolan
President Eduardo dos Santos and UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that an absolute safe environment should
be created to ensure smooth reconstruction of national power
grassroots all over the country.
</P>
<P>
It also advised that the former rebel UNITA movement should
disband all its soldiers who are still outside the quartering
camps.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the ruling party appealed to the United
Nations to take its responsibilities under the Lusaka Peace
Agreement and authorized by UN the Security Council for the
smooth undergoing of the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
The national congress of the MPLA was opened here on
Tuesday and ended today. More than 800 delegates from the
country's 18 provinces had focused their discussions on the peace
process and economic and social issues in Angola. 
