<HEADLINE> Envoy Says U.N. Ready to Help Cypriot Bi-Communal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations will help the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides overcome their differences in
searching for a comprehensive settlement in next week's direct
negotiations near New York, a U.N. envoy said here today.
</P>
<P>
Telling reporters at Larnaca Airport before leaving for New
York, U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel said
the U.N. is ready to help the two sides with ideas and proposals
depending on the problems they encounter.
</P>
<P>
"We should not prejudge or anticipate what is going to happen"
at the direct negotiations between Cyprus President Glafcos
Clrides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, due to begin
July 9, said Feissel, who is also to take part in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Feissel added the U.N.'s first concern in the negotiations is
to resolve the protracted Cyprus problem, but any
confidence-building measures which may flow out the talks will be
fostered.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy noted that both Clerides and Denktash are fully
aware of the responsibilities they bear as they travel to New York
for the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Denktash left today for New York from Turkey where he
discussed with Turkish leaders the strategy he will follow in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Clerides will leave Sunday for New York via London. Earlier
this week, he visited Athens where he discussed developments on
Cyprus issue with Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis prior to the
New York talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored Cyprus peace talks aim at reuniting this
Eastern Mediterranean island under a bizonal, bicommunal
federation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
