<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges Arab Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri today renewed his call for tightening up economic ties
within the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
He made the call at the Egyptian-Jordanian Higher Committee
meeting that opened here this evening at the cabinet premises
under the co-chairmanship of Ganzouri and his Jordanian
counterpart Abdul Salam Majali.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri called upon the Arabs to work for attaining a solid
economic base by strengthening inter-Arab exchange.
</P>
<P>
He also underlined the necessity of creating an Arab common
market in context of continuous international developments.
</P>
<P>
"Arab countries that have partnership with European countries
and the U.S. should first embark on partnership with the Arab
countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade among the Arab countries stands only less
than 10 percent of their total foreign trade, while Arabs have
directed merely 15 percent of their investments within their own
world, Ganzouri noted.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Trade, Industry and Supply Hani Moulki
today also called for an Arab common market that can face up to
world economic pressures following his meeting this afternoon with
Egyptian Minister of Economy and International Cooperation Nawal
Tatawi.
</P>
<P>
Ten Jordanian ministers arrived here today for the 14th
Egyptian-Jordanian Higher Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Altogether six agreements and protocols of cooperation between
Egypt and Jordan in economic and cultural fields are expected to
be signed during the two-day committee meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
