<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Going on North of Kabul, Northern Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia today
claimed having gained some ground north of Kabul, but admitted
they were yet to capture the key highway town of Jabul Siraj.
</P>
<P>
Taliban sources in Peshawar, Pakistan's northwestern major
city, said the Islamic militia had captured five villages east of
Jabul Siraj, a much contested strategic center about 80 km north
of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban launched an attack this morning on positions held
by the forces loyal to former military chief Ahmad Masood, who
grabbed Jabul Siraj from the Taliban's hands in late May, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
About 30 people from both sides were killed in the fighting
which was still going on, and the Taliban captured 80 Masood's
men, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources also confirmed that the fighting between the
Taliban and northern opposition forces were still going on in
Kunduz and Faryeb provinces.
</P>
<P>
Recently, fighting has been raging on several fronts, north of
the Afghan capital, in northwestern Faryab province and in the
northern province of Kunduz.
</P>
<P>
However, both the Taliban and the northern opposition forces
have made only minor territorial gains.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has asked for a ceasefire, but both sides
have refused.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban are demanding the release of its high-ranking
officials being held prisoner in northern Afghanistan before
negotiating an end to the fighting.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban coalition, led by Masood and Uzbek warlord
Abdul Malik, is demanding the demilitarization of Kabul before
they could agree to a ceasefire.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
