<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's New Combat Force on Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,500 soldiers and 900
vehicles paraded in the coastal city of Brisbane today in one of
the largest gatherings of Australian combat forces since the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
Army Chief General John Sanderson told the troops that the
parade marked the beginning of an era in which the army would
build a modern, dynamic high technology force for the defense of
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The occasion marked the first official gathering of the 7th
Task Force, which represents the first step in the Army's
restructuring program, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The new unit comprises soldiers, vehicles and guns which today
spread over most of the parade ground at the Enoggera army base in
Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
The 7th Task Force is an amalgamation of the old Brisbane-based
6th and 7th Brigades and was formed to create a single integrated
unit complete with its own armor, artillery, transport and support
elements.
</P>
<P>
"It's planned as the forerunner of a total of seven task forces
and a special operations group which will make up the Australian
army of the 21st century," the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
"The 3,000-plus soldiers you see on parade represent about
three quarters of the largest combat formation Australia has had
since the Vietnam war," General Sanderson said.
</P>
<P>
"It is our objective to build and equip seven such task forces
and a special forces group over the next decade".
</P>
<P>
"This will provide a potent and versatile foundation for
Australian continental defense and also provide the nation with a
range of options to contribute to global and regional security
should this be necessary," the army chief said.
</P>
<P>
He said units making up the task force would have to operate
over great distances and be more self-reliant with greater and
more precise firepower than ever before.
</P>
<P>
Defense spending represents 1.9 percent of Australia's gross
domestic product, a figure which Defense Minister Ian McLachlan
has indicated will have to start increasing soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
