<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilians Wounded in Israeli Bombardment in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Three civilians were wounded today
in violent Israeli bombardment of a heights opposite the Israeli
self-proclaimed "security zone" in south Lebanon, which came in
retaliation for a guerrilla attack on an Israeli patrol, security
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The anonymous security sources in south Lebanon said that
Israeli artillery fired more than 100 shells in a couple of hours
at Iglim Al-Toffah, or Province of Apple, some 65 kilometers
southeast of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
A seven-year-old boy and two others were injured when their
village of Ain Buswar was hit by several 120mm and 155mm heavy
shells, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Apachi helicopters also carried out a series of air
raids on the heights, which is often used by guerrillas as a
springboard to launch attacks on the Israeli-occupied buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas of the Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of
God, ambushed an Israeli foot patrol near the town of Sujoud in
the central sector of the border strip earlier this morning.
</P>
<P>
A Hezbollah statement said that all elements of the Israeli
patrol were killed or wounded.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia
said that one Israeli soldier was killed. But the Lebanese
security sources stressed that two Israeli soldiers died as a
result of the guerrilla offensive.
</P>
<P>
The escalation came on the eve of a meeting of a five-nation
panel to look into two complaints filed by Lebanon and Israel
respectively accusing each other of violating a cease-fire
understanding the two countries reached in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the
United States, who make up the cease-fire monitoring committee,
is to hold the meeting in the south Lebanese border town of
Naqoura Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 ostensibly to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
