<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Fewer Palestinians Apply for Visitors' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of Palestinians
abroad visiting relatives in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip
this summer will be very small compared with that of previous
years, according to a report of The Jerusalem Times.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian English weekly newspaper quoted Muhammad
Hussein, head of the Palestinian Passport Department, as saying
this week that the down-slide trend is due to Israeli measures,
which have grown stricter than ever.
</P>
<P>
Hussein said that back in 1995 Israel gave permits to 35,000
applicants, but discouraged by the conditions created by the
Jewish state, the number of applicants has dropped drastically
this year.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we have received only 16,000 application forms of
which Israel has approved a mere 2,500," he said.
</P>
<P>
In explaining the limited number of applicants in 1997, the
Under-secretary of the Palestinian Ministry of Civil Affairs,
Freij Kheiri, said that the visitors were frustrated by the
discomforts experienced throughout the journey.
</P>
<P>
"For one, there is the interminable wait at the crossing
points which could take up to 36 hours before travelers continue
their journey. And this applies to both arrivals and
departures. Secondly, there is nowhere they can rest properly," he
elaborated.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the journey was made especially uncomfortable
because the buses conveying the visitors from Jordan to the Gaza
Strip were accompanied throughout the journey by Israeli police
who kept them under close observation.
</P>
<P>
Kheiri condemned Israel's policy and called it a violation of
the Oslo Accords, which state that Palestinians abroad could
visit their relatives any time they wish.
</P>
<P>
"This is a policy of collective punishment, aimed at stifling
the Palestinians economically, politically, and socially, all of
which contradicts basic human rights," he added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian economists consider the summer visits by
Palestinians abroad to be a sizable source of revenues for the
Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
The visitors may spend millions of U.S. dollars to purchase
real estate, and considerable amounts on entertainment, apart
from the financial help they extend to their relatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
