<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan Sets Minimum Living Standard for Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan Province
decreed a bottom-line living standard for its farmers in May this
year.
</P>
<P>
According to the system, those who live under the poverty level
will receive aid from the government to enable them to reach the
standard.
</P>
<P>
This is an important step in the establishment of a multi-tier
social security network throughout the country, according to
central government officials.
</P>
<P>
The funds for this will be jointly provided by the relevant
county, township and village authorities.
</P>
<P>
Henan is the province with the largest population in China. Of
its more than 90 million people, 4.9 million are living in
poverty, which means that they do not have sufficient food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
At present, the basic living standard set for the province's
farmers is between 450 and 500 yuan (about 60 US dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
The standard is based on local prices and consumption level,
provincial officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu Tackling Township Enterprise Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu Province
has mapped out a plan to reduce pollution emitted by township
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The plan mainly targets paper-making, tanning and cement-making
enterprises, which are the worst polluters.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, 30 paper mills each having an annual production
capacity of over 5,000 tons, 40 leather enterprises each having an
annual manufacturing capacity of 30,000 hides and 50 cement plants
will be technologically upgraded.
</P>
<P>
These enterprises are expected to reduce their sewage discharge
by seven million tons before the year 2000 and improve their
sewage treatment rate to more than 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
There are some 600 small-scale township enterprises in the
province engaged in oil refining, paper making, tanning, and lead
and zinc processing.
</P>
<P>
The provincial authorities started to tackle the pollution
caused by these enterprises last year, and have closed down or
diverted the operations of 538 of them.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they have banned the introduction of pulp-making
equipment using chemical techniques with a production capacity of
less than 10,000 tons, and urged paper mills which have an annual
capacity of more than 5,000 tons but less than 10,000 tons each to
merge their operations with other factories, in a bid to reduce
pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
