<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM: Jordan to Side With Arabs on Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali suggested today his country might not attend the Doha
economic conference if no progress is made on the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Majali made the statement to reporters after his meeting with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak this morning, according to the
Egypt's Middle East news agency (MENA).
</P>
<P>
"Talk about this conference depends on circumstances and on
the peace process. We hope the peace process could be revived so
that the economic conference can resume," he said.
</P>
<P>
Majali said Jordan would side with other Arab countries in
deciding whether or not to participate in such a regional meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan will not separate from other Arabs," he said, echoing
the statement by Jordanian Minister of Industry, Trade and Supply
Hani Moulki Saturday that his country might retreat its former
decision to attend the fourth Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
economic conference.
</P>
<P>
"My country has previously declared its approval to take part
in the conference but it eventually sides with the Arab stance,"
said Moulki, who and other nine Jordanian ministers are here for
the 14th Jordanian-Egyptian Higher Committee meetings.
</P>
<P>
Discouraged by the lack of a breakthrough in the deadlocked
peace process, several Arab countries have decided to boycott the
Doha meeting, which Israel will attend. Egypt has yet to announce
its own decision.
</P>
<P>
Morocco, Jordan and Egypt have hosted the previous three MENA
economic conferences separately in Casablanca, in 1994, in Amman,
in 1995 and in Cairo, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Majali also expressed support for the Egyptian efforts to
revive the deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian premier said the Israeli leadership is still
intransigent and unaware that no permanent peace can be
established without returning the Arab lands to their owners and
without setting up a Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its
capital.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the Arab nation sides with these views," Majali
said. The western world also sides with these ideas and is now
embracing the Palestinian issue due to the Israeli intransigence,
he added.
</P>
<P>
No permanent peace will be established without Syria, Lebanon
or the Palestinians, the Jordanian premier stressed.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he conveyed to Mubarak a message from King
Hussein of Jordan and is taking a reply message back to the king.
</P>
<P>
His meeting with the Egyptian president dealt with three main
issues, namely bilateral ties on all levels, inter-Arab relations
and the peace process, according to the MENA report.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt, the only two Arab countries to have made
peace with Israel, have played important mediating roles in the
Mideast peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0046 </DOCNO>
