<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia: Firewood Collecting Women Lead Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 15,000 women in Addis
Ababa earn their miserable livelihood by selling firewood.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed here today by the Office of the Project for
Firewood Carrier Women, which is engaged in jointly conducting
the study with the World Labor Organization and the Ministry of
Labor and Social Affairs of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, the firewood collecting women, earning
below 65 Birr (9.6 U.S. Dollars) per month, are among the
low-income group in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
They are aged between 10 and 19 and have to travel about 30
kilometers on foot to deliver the firewood to customers. They
carry about 35 kilograms of firewood which in most cases is
overweight.
</P>
<P>
These women are providing a third of the demand for firewood
in the metropolis which has a population of several million.
</P>
<P>
The study said the destitute women are engaged in illegal
activity since they cause depletion of forests in the suburbs
of Addis.
</P>
<P>
The study is to identify an alternative income generating
means for the poor women besides helping them take part in
afforestation.
</P>
<P>
Plans have been drawn to offer the women training and later
extend loan services in a bid to help them to be self-supportive,
the study added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
