<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Open Embassy in Algiers: Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The South African government will
open an embassy soon in Algiers, which will be a vehicle to boost
links and trade, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said during a visit
in the Algerian capital today.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki made the disclosure after talks with Algerian Premier
Ahmed Ouyahia in which both agreed on steps to boost cooperation
and trade links, according to a report from the official Algerian
News Agency APS.
</P>
<P>
The two sides "reasserted their determination to reinforce and
consolidate links of friendship and cooperation existing between
the two countries,'' Mbeki and Ouyahia said in a joint
communique.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to set up a joint cooperation committee and work
on finalizing agreements of interest to both sides, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki held talks with president liamine zeroual and several
other algerian leaders before leaving algiers today at the end of
a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The South African leader visited Tunisia earlier in the week
and is expected to arrive in Mali today. His trip is focused on
developing diplomatic and trade relations with the three African
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
