<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Russia to Conduct Joint Astronomy Experiment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- An Indo-Russian gamma-ray
astronomy experiment on the Russian satellite mission "Photon" is
expected to be launched by next year, said Chairman of the Indian
Space Research Organization (ISRO) K. Kasturirangan today.
</P>
<P>
The mission would study the temporal and spectral
characteristics of the sun and gamma-ray bursts in both high and
low energy ranges. The galactic and extragalactic objects and
sites, and the galactic diffuse background would also come under
experiment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The mission's gamma-ray astronomy payload has been built
jointly by India's Tata Institute of Fundamental Research and
Russian scientists.
</P>
<P>
The instrument consists of a low energy and a high energy
gamma-ray telescope, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
