<HEADLINE> Protestants Begin March in N. Ireland, Tension High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 500 Protestants began their
annual parade this morning in Northern Ireland as hundreds of
British troops and police took up control of the march route.
</P>
<P>
Riot police were reported to have seized control of main roads
in Portadown in Northern Ireland early today in one of the biggest
security operations in 28 years of conflict.
</P>
<P>
The troops were on high alert to guard against any trouble
after weeks of controversy over plans by the Protestant Orange
Order to hold an annual parade which will go through the Roman
Catholic-controlled zone later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said at
a press conference that a decision to allow an Orange Order parade
along the Catholic Garvaghy Road of Portadown as "a sad day for
all of us."
</P>
<P>
"Many people will be angry with what has occurred and I ask for
restraint," she said.
</P>
<P>
The pro-British Orange Order says the parades are peaceful
celebrations, but the Catholic Irish nationalists, who wish to end
the British rule over the Northern Ireland, were strongly opposed
to the parade, arguing the march shows intimidation to the
Catholic residents.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that in the dead of the night, some of the
Catholic protesters sat on the road but police officers kept
advancing, raising their see-through riot shields to fend off a
hail of bottles and stones hurled by youngsters on the
pavement. Police even fired plastic bullets and injured several
Catholic residents.
</P>
<P>
But the clashes subsided as dawn broke, revealing the full
panoply of armored vehicle power along the disputed roadway.
</P>
<P>
Last year, police prevented the marchers from going through the
Catholic enclave but changed their decision after days of
Protestant rioting and sparked Catholic fury instead.
</P>
<P>
Dozen more Protestant parades will be staged until July 12, the
most cherished date in the Orange calendar which marks a 17th
century Protestant victory over Britain's last Catholic
King. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Split over Enlargement Pace Overshadows NATO Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the 16 member states of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) will endorse the
eastward expansion at their Madrid summit to be held on July 8 and
9, but split over which countries should join the military
alliance in the first wave overshadows the summit.
</P>
<P>
The leaders have planned to unveil a new military organization
that will have closer ties with its partner countries and provide
a balanced power-sharing system within the alliance, thus making
the so-called European Security and Defense Identity more visible.
</P>
<P>
As they prepare for it, the item atop their agenda is not
whether NATO should expand, but which countries should be admitted.
</P>
<P>
A serious row has emerged between the United States and its
European allies over which countries to invite to join NATO in
the Madrid summit.
</P>
<P>
On June 12, the Clinton Administration announced, under the
pressure from the U.S. Congress, that Washington would support only
three countries - Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic - to join
NATO in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. position has reportedly gained support from four NATO
member states -- Iceland, Britain, Norway and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
But France, supported by eight other NATO member states
predominately from southern Europe, has lobbied hard for the
candidacies of Romania and Slovenia as well, in an effort to
avoid too heavy a shift in NATO's future orientation toward
Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
Germany and the Netherlands have taken a flexible stance on
this issue. German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said on Wednesday after
meeting with Romanian President Emil Constantinescu in Bonn that
he was in favor of Romania's entry "soon".
</P>
<P>
But a German official said "it would be a misinterpretation of
his remarks to take 'soon' to mean at the NATO summit. There is no
fixed date."
</P>
<P>
Both Germany and the Netherlands are expected to fall in with
Washington eventually, a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
However, most European allies are somehow disturbed by what
some see as an American attempt to "dictate" to them who will be
admitted as new members of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac and other European leaders seem
to fear that the U.S. will attempt to turn the Madrid summit into
an event that combines holding a beauty contest for potential
members and a crowning of the U.S. president as king of the
NATO, an article in the International Herald Tribune commented.
</P>
<P>
Some hopes were being expressed that the Americans will back
down in part by agreeing to let Slovenia join the alliance in the
first wave.
</P>
<P>
However, that has been rejected by U.S. diplomatic
sources. They said that if Washington relented towards Slovenia,
"that would make it even worse for Romania".
</P>
<P>
Clinton said early this week that he did not foresee any
circumstances under which he would change his mind on limiting the
first wave expansion to three.
</P>
<P>
While reaffirming that five countries now fulfilled the
conditions for joining, France indicated in a statement on July 2
that it would not block the admission of only three countries if
Clinton insisted.
</P>
<P>
The statement, one NATO diplomat in Brussels explained, was
France's way of putting the onus on the United States to explain
to Romania and Slovenia why they could not be admitted together
with the three others.
</P>
<P>
Other NATO member states supporting the two countries would
probably follow France's example and accept Clinton's preference,
the same diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
These countries are also hoping that even if Washington refuses
to yield, it might agree to a form of words in the Madrid
communique that would make clear that Romania and Slovenia would
be guaranteed membership in the second wave "a year or two" after
the first entrants had joined, at NATO's 50th anniversary in April
1999.
</P>
<P>
A possible compromise deal to end the U.S.-Europe diplomatic
feuding could involve Austria abandoning its neutrality and
joining, alongside Romania and Slovenia in 2001, some experts
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Senior NATO sources in Brussels are increasingly confident that
Austria is poised to abandon half a century of neutrality and
apply for NATO membership later this year.
</P>
<P>
NATO's foreign ministers plan to meet in Madrid on Monday to
hammer out a stand. If those talks fail, the issue will be taken
up by the leaders on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some experts fear that even if the Americans get away at the
summit, this split will sow the seeds of future difficulties in
the relationship between the United States and its European
allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
