<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Clashes Foretell New Intifadah: Hebron Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Head of Hebron Municipality Mostafa
el-Natshah termed today the present clashes between Palestinians
and Israeli forces as a sign of the eruption of a new Intifadah
(uprising).
</P>
<P>
In an interview this morning with the Egyptian Voice of Arabs
radio, Natshah said that confrontation between the two sides will
continue until the Israeli government honors its commitments to
the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the escalated confrontations to the Israeli
government's insistence on going ahead with its settlement policy
and Israeli settlers' provocative practices.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Islamic posters that were circulated in the West Bank
city of Hebron recently were only the latest of such provocations,
the Palestinian official added.
</P>
<P>
Hebron has long been the showcase of the Israeli-Palestinian
confrontations. Since Israeli troops redeployed from 80 percent of
Hebron under an agreement signed in January, about 450 Jewish
settlers have remained living in the city heavily guarded by
Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of violence in the volatile city was sparked
last Saturday by the distribution of leaflets depicting Islam's
Prophet Mohammed as a pig writing the holy Koran by a rightist
Jewish woman from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The violence broke out against the backdrop of prolonged
deadlock of Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. The talks collapsed
in March as Israel began building a new settlement in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) is demanding an halt
to the settlement activities as a precondition for resuming the
talks, while Israel asks the PNA to resume security cooperation
and crack down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Despite mediation efforts by the U.S. and Egypt, the wide gap
remains between the two sides, leading to fears about escalation
of violence in the Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
