<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Scientists Engineer Animals Possible of Making Human Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- British scientists are using the
revolutionary clone technology to engineer animals which will
generate the key proteins and antibodies in human plasma.
</P>
<P>
The new technique will provide a steady supply of cheap safe
blood products worth up to 1.5 billion pounds (about 2.4 billion
U.S. dollars) a year, The Observer said today.
</P>
<P>
Surgeons and hospital administrators, struggling to overcome
blood shortages, have welcomed the breakthrough, saying it could
save lives and help prevent the spread of blood-born viruses such
as HIV and hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
PPL Therapeutics, the Edinburgh firm supporting the program, is
creating cows and sheep with human DNA. Scientists use "chemical
scissors" to remove or alter the animals' blood plasma -- albumen,
clotting factors and antibodies.
</P>
<P>
Scientists plan to rear herds of the animals and extract the
proteins from their milk before mixing them to create plasma.
</P>
<P>
Cheap, reliable supplies of plasma are vital when dealing with
patients who have lost a lot of blood, and health professionals
welcomed the breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
The Observer quoted Charles Collins, a member of the Royal
College of Surgeons` council, as saying "this is of major
importance. The production of large amounts of cheap plasma would
greatly help doctors, surgeons and paramedics to stabilize and
treat patients."
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the technique could eventually lead to
animals producing blood containing natural human antibodies to
help fight diseases including cystic fibrosis, haemophilia,
osteoporosis and some cancers.
</P>
<P>
However, scientists argue that extensive trials to ensure the
safety of the products could take years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
