<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Army Chief Reportedly to Retire Earlier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- There are conflicting reports
over the future of Israeli Army Chief of Staff Amnon Shahak, who
reportedly has decided not to extend his term due to disputes with
the government.
</P>
<P>
Israeli private television Channel 2 reported Saturday night
that Shahak, in an unprecedented move, would not seek to have his
term extended to a full fourth year due to his discontent with his
working relationship with Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The report said Shahak was to inform Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai that he was not interested in extending his term when
they meet later this week to discuss Shahak's future in the army.
</P>
<P>
Shahak is likely to step down on Israel's 50th independence
day next year, seven months before his fourth year in office ends,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
But Israel Radio reported this morning that Shahak had denied
the report, saying no meeting has been set between him and
Mordechai. "The report did not come from the chief of staff and
did not reflect his opinion," a statement released by an army
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Ministry spokesman also said that Mordechai had not
yet concluded the appointments in the army's general staff.
</P>
<P>
If the television report proves true, it would be the first
time that a chief of staff does not seek a fourth year, which has
traditionally been taken as granted.
</P>
<P>
It remained unclear whether it was the disappointment with the
prolonged deadlock in the peace process, in addition to the tense
relationship with the Netanyahu government, that had led to
Shahak's decision to retire from the army earlier.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after Netanyahu's election victory last year,
rumors surfaced that Shahak and other top members of the general
staff, such as his deputy Matan Vilnai, would resign if Yitzhak
Mordechai was named Defense Minister.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, a former army commander, was reportedly angered at
Shahak and Vilnai for taking posts that he had wanted before he
decided to retire from the army to enter politics.
</P>
<P>
However, after being named as the defense minister, Mordechai
has made great efforts to defuse tensions with the general staff
and succeeded in fostering good working relations with them.
</P>
<P>
If Shahak indeed retires, the speculation is that Mordechai
will have no choice but to recommend to the government that
Vilnai replace Shahak. Another possible candidate for the post
is the head of Army Planning Branch Shaul Mofaz, a former head
of the Southern Command. 
</P>
</TEXT>
