<HEADLINE> Saudi King Enlarges Consultative Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 6 (Xinhua) -- King Fahd ibn Abdul-Aziz of
Saudi Arabia has issued a decree to increase the number of the
consultative Shura council members to 91 from the current 60.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here from the Saudi city of Jeddah said today
that the decree issued Saturday by the king states that "the Shura
council will be made of 90 members and one president."
</P>
<P>
The Shura council, set up in 1993, is a consultative body in
charge of making suggestions and advices to the Saudi monarch to
help run the state affairs. It members are appointed by the King.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd, since the start of this year, issued several royal
decrees on the state system covering the Council of Ministers, the
Shura Council and the formation of assemblies as part of the
kingdom's drive to improve the administration of the
country. 
</P>
