<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Pollees Feel Japan's Safety Level Crumbling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of Japanese believed
that the country is not as safe as it used to be, said a survey
released recently by a leading Japanese newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was conducted by Yomiuri Shimbun on June 21
and 22, randomly selected 3,000 eligible voters across the
country. The response rate was 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 81 percent of respondents said that
they felt the safety level in Japan deteriorating in the past
several years, while 15 percent said the condition had improved.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 sarin nerve gas attack on the Tokyo subway system, the
increasing number of crimes committed by illegal aliens and the
rising number of violent crimes by young offenders were cited as
evidence of the deterioration of public order in Japan, which
used to be the safest country among the developed nations.
</P>
<P>
Asked to specify the kinds of crimes most likely to affect them
or members of their families, 36 percent of the pollees cited
crank calls, 33 percent cited fraud and illegal marketing, and 31
percent cited random crimes.
</P>
<P>
Growing concerns about crimes made the respondents call for
tighter controls by the law enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
As many as 55 percent of respondents approved of the recent
policy change by the National Police Agency to arrest young
offenders rather than to "protect" them. Forty-one percent of the
pollees said such a change was unavoidable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
