<HEADLINE> Hingis Snatches her First Wimbledon Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- World number one tennis player
Martina Hingis of Switzerland snatched her first Wimbledon women's
singles title here today after beating Czech tennis veteran Jana
Novotna in a three-set battle 2-6 6-3 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Novotna, 1993 Wimbledon finalist, opened the final clash with a
flying form by breaking two consecutive games of Hingis and ran
away with the first 6:2 in less than 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, a 1994 Wimbledon junior champion and a doubles winner
in 1996, staged patient counterattacks in the second set and
gradually gained an upper hand over the 28-year-old Novotna, who
was suffering from an strained stomach muscle.
</P>
<P>
With the second set in her pocket, the 16-year-old tennis
genius displayed dazzaling tennis and wholly dominated and won the
third set in a convincing manner.
</P>
<P>
Explaining her failure today, Novotna said: "I came into the
match with a bit of injury. It was pulled abdominal stomach
muscle."
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, I had a little bit of pain in the second set
and it got worse and worse as the match progressed," she added.
</P>
<P>
Novotna also paid tribute to her younger opponent by saying
"She's so normal. When she is not on court she acts like a normal
teenage kid, but on the other hand she knows very well what she is
doing. When she's out there she wants to win and she has the
advantage that she has so much variety in her game."
</P>
<P>
Hingis, the youngest Wimbledon champion in 110 years, told
reporters after the match: "I felt like a beginner. I did not play
badly. She was just all over the net."
</P>
<P>
The smiling Hingis noted "two different players came together
in this game and she's aggressive, I'm defensive. I did it this
time, She could win next time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
