<HEADLINE> Link Between Skin Conditions, Infertility Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli gynecologist
has concluded that hirsutism, overweight and acne in teenage
girls are a warning sign that they may suffer later from
polycystic ovary syndrome and have serious fertility problems,
reported The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Roy Homberg, senior gynecologist at the Rabin Medical
Center, reported his research results at a recent conference of
endocrinologists and dermatologists.
</P>
<P>
He noted that dermatologists are often the first specialists
girls consult in teenage years.
</P>
<P>
When the problem is that there is too much hair on the body
and acne, they should look into the possibility of this syndrome,
a disorder marked by a failure to ovulate or menstruate and an
inability to become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
It is caused by the endocrine gland getting out of balance,
with higher levels of some hormones such as testosterone and
estrogen and lower levels of follicle-stimulating hormone.
</P>
<P>
The latter causes the ovarian follicles to grow only
partially, and they do not release eggs.
</P>
<P>
The ovary often grows to twice the size of a normal ovary and
is covered by a smooth, pearly-white capsule.
</P>
<P>
The treatment includes giving female hormones or surgical
removal of the affected ovary. Dermatologists should be on the
lookout, for the pattern of symptoms in early adolescence.
</P>
<P>
Proper treatment can save considerable misery, not only in
dealing with infertility, but also with diabetes and high blood
cholesterol, which in older women are also part of this
syndrome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
