<HEADLINE> Dhaka Forms Interim Council in Hill District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
constituted a five-member interim local government council for
Khagrachhari hill district, one of the three troubled southern
hill districts, following the extended term of the elected body
expired on July 4.
</P>
<P>
According to an official handout here today, the new committee
took over charge at a simple ceremony at the district local
government office on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
However, interim committees for the other two hill districts,
Bandarban and Rangamati, could not be formed for court injunction.
</P>
<P>
A High Court Division bench has placed an embargo on the
government, following a writ filed by the two councils, in
appointing interim committee for the hill districts.
</P>
<P>
The government in 1989 introduced the local government council
system for the three districts in Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT).
The councils for the hill districts were installed that year
through direct elections for a three-year term.
</P>
<P>
But, due to unrest triggered by tribal insurgency in the CHT, a
second election to the local government could not yet be held.
</P>
<P>
After the expiry of the elected committees in 1992, the
government had extended their term five times. The parliament
passed a bill early this year, empowering the government to
appoint an interim committee to replace the original councils in
the CHT.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said new election to the local government
councils of the CHT would be held in a peaceful atmosphere after a
solution of the CHT problem through signing agreement with the
tribal rebels.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to hold the next round of talks on
July 14 with the tribal insurgents, who have been fighting about
two decades for the self-rule of the resource-rich hill areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
