<HEADLINE> Law Needed in India to Stop U.S. Bio-piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Indian experts have time and
again called for enacting new laws in the country so as to stop
U.S. bio-piracy, the National Herald said here today.
</P>
<P>
The developed nations, the United States in particular, "have
been thieving away our resource-rich bio-diversity for decades
now. It is said that the gene-bank in the U.S. have stored almost
90 percent genes of our plant and animal resources. And this loot
will go on and on unless a stringent law is put in place at the
soonest to end it," the paper quoted experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This is what the U.S. does not want. In order to put pressure
on India not to enact such a law, the U.S. government has been
bullying her to accept the unequal intellectual property rights
treaty," it further said.
</P>
<P>
"India is endowed by nature with a rich bio-diversity of 45,000
plants and 95,000 animal species... ninety percent of plant
species have already been patented by outside agencies without
least assertion of ownership rights by the Indian states," it
said.
</P>
<P>
"If this genetic loot is to be stopped forthwith, New Delhi
must immediately enact a stringent law to make such thieving a
cognizable offense. Not doing so is not only posing an economic
threat to our country but is also putting at risk the livelihood
of millions of our countrymen," it stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
