<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Increase Green Food Production Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build 10 additional
green food production bases nationwide by the year of 2000, which
will both increase farmers' income and promote agricultural
growth, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Known as organic or natural food in the west, green food means
high-quality, nutritious agricultural products with low content of
chemical fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Green foods are usually sold at prices 10 percent higher than
regular food in China.
</P>
<P>
Li Lintao, an official with the China Green Food Development
Center, said that the 10 major cities with such production bases
include Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
The center was accepted as a member of the International
Federation of Organic Agriculture Movements in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He said that the center is now seeking support from local
governments, to have more farmers to produce green food.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the bases will provide technological service to
local farmers.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Vegetable Production Base in the capital's eastern
suburb covers an area of 13.3 hectares, and earns a total of 2.5
million yuan in profits every year.
</P>
<P>
He said that China had had 712 kinds of green food products by
the end of 1996, and the industry's output value reached 15
billion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
Only 0.1 percent of the country's cultivated land have been
allocated for green food production, Li said, adding the figure is
expected to hit one percent by the end of this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In Memory of the Marco Polo Bridge Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1997 sees the 60th
anniversary of the Marco Polo Bridge Incident, which militarist
Japan provoked to wage its all-out war of aggression against China.
</P>
<P>
As an old Chinese saying goes: "Past experience, if not
forgotten, is a guide for the future." Therefore, today, it is
absolutely necessary to look back upon Japanese militarists' war
of aggression against China and to draw a profound lesson from it.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary because there has always existed a small
right-wing force in Japan which denies Japan's history of
aggression.
</P>
<P>
Those people became even more active in recent years,
intensifying their efforts to eulogize and whitewash Japanese
militarism and tried hard to reverse the verdict on Japan's
invasion of other Asian nations, including China.
</P>
<P>
They said Japan was defending its "legitimate rights" when it
forced the 21 Demands on China in 1915, which was aimed at
dominating China, and when it launched the September 18 Incident
in 1931, which was a significant step toward Japan's occupation of
the entire northeast of China.
</P>
<P>
They claimed the Marco Polo Bridge Incident was not created by
the Japanese side and instead was the work of the Chinese troops.
</P>
<P>
They even alleged the Rape of Nanjing (Nanking) in 1937 was
"merely fabrication."
</P>
<P>
By these remarks of utmost absurdity, they distorted history to
the utmost degree, thus severely hurting the feelings of the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Their moves cannot but make people highly vigilant. What on
earth do they intend to?
</P>
<P>
Opening the historical records which are not yet dust-laden, we
can easily find that Japan's invasion and occupation of China was
a long-premediated ambition of the Japanese militarists.
</P>
<P>
The notorious (Giichi) Tanaka Memorial to the Throne in 1927
revealed Japan's ambition of annexing China as part of its
strategy to conquer and dominate the world as early as in the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
It was under the strategy of the Tanaka memorial -- "to conquer
China, we must first conquer Manchuria and Mongolia; to conquer
the whole world, we must first conquer China" -- that the Japanese
militarists provoked the September 18 Incident and concocted the
so-called Manchuria state within China.
</P>
<P>
It was under the same strategy that, Japan, after deliberate
planning, created the Marco Polo Bridge Incident on July 7, 1937
and later spread the flames of war to more than two thirds of
Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
During the war, Japanese aggressor troops desperately
implemented the policy of "kill all, loot all and burn all" on
Chinese soil, and even used biological and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The atrocities that Japan inflicted upon China were the most
barbarous and most brutal in human history.
</P>
<P>
Japan's aggression against China was unprecedented in human
history in terms of duration, scale and damage.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, as many as 35 million Chinese
were killed or wounded during the war of aggression.
</P>
<P>
Calculated by the exchange rates of 1937, the direct damage
which Japan caused to China reached as high as 100 billion
U.S. dollars, while the indirect damage 500 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The monstrous crime that Japanese militarists committed in
China, human testimony and material evidence which is still there
will by no means disappear with the mere disavowals of a handful
of Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The more they try to cover it up, the more the crime will be
exposed. What the small group of Japanese are doing will only
make the already shameful historical records of Japan all the more
disgusting.
</P>
<P>
These people who are trying to reverse the historical verdict
may not realize that they are functioning as teachers by negative
example. Consequently, people have removed the scales from their
eyes, and are able to see that in Japan there indeed exists a
small group of right-wing forces ready to make trouble with
ulterior motives.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing forces may be thin in manpower, but their energy
and influence should never be underestimated. Therefore they
deserve high vigilance.
</P>
<P>
To adopt a correct view of history is the political basis for
the development of Sino-Japanese relations. It is also the
starting point for the establishment of mutual trust between the
two countries and an essential precondition to friendship between
the two nations from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
To admit rather than deny that period of history when Japan
inflicted atrocities on China is a matter of principle.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, a few people in Japan, overtly or covertly,
have accused China of repeatedly picking on Japan on the issue of
history.
</P>
<P>
But, as a matter of fact, since the end of the war, the Chinese
side has always held that the two countries should look forward in
developing bilateral relations, and that there should be a
distinction between Japanese militarists and the broad masses of
Japanese people, who also suffered from the war of aggression.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five years ago, China buried old grudges with Japan and
resumed diplomatic relations with it, in the hope that the
unpleasant page of history could be forever turned over.
</P>
<P>
However, the tree may crave calm, but the wind will not stop.
A small group of Japanese repeatedly stirred up trouble after the
resumption of Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations. Consequently,
the spirit of the 1972 Sino-Japanese Joint Statement was profaned
and the feelings of the Chinese people were severely hurt. Only
under such circumstances was the Chinese side compelled to make
necessary reactions.
</P>
<P>
Facts show that the issue of history does not re-emerge from
time to time because the Chinese people are fond of bringing up
matters of the past, still less that the Chinese people like to
continually pick on Japan. The crux of the problem is quite clear.
</P>
<P>
Even today, a handful of Japanese are advocating reactionary
militarist historical views in an attempt to reverse the verdict
on Japan's history of aggression.
</P>
<P>
Their remarks and activities bring troubles not only to China
but also to Japan and the Japanese people, because their words and
deeds do not conform to the historical views of the Japanese
people and their common wishes to develop friendship with China.
In fact, they are obstructing and sabotaging the development of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan should join their efforts to oppose and stop
such activities, to strictly abide by the 1972 Joint Statement and
the 1978 Treaty of Peace and Friendship to guarantee the sound and
stable development of bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
