<HEADLINE> First Farmer's Banking Office Set up in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 6 (Xinhua) -- With a view to eradicating
poverty in the rural areas, the first banking office run by
farmers in Nepal was set up Saturday in Dhading district, about 40
kilometers west of here.
</P>
<P>
The starting of the banking office by a group of farmers
through cooperative institutions is significant, it is very useful
for the farmers saving small amount of money for improving living
standard and the development of the district, said Nepali Finance
Minister Rabindra Nath Sharma when inaugurating the banking
office.
</P>
<P>
Through the so-called "Small Farmers Banking Office", farmers
could exploit maximum resources, saving more money and utilizing
them in productive activities, noted Sharma.
</P>
<P>
Devendra Pratap Shaha, acting general manager of the Nepali
Agricultural Development Bank (ADB), promised to work more for the
welfare of farmers by expanding the small farmers' development
programs all over the country to wipe out poverty from grassroots
level, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Farmers speaking on the occasion demanded more facilities from
the country's central bank and the ADB as well as donors for
sustaining farmers' projects in the long run.
</P>
<P>
The farmers' banking office had collected some 1.51 million
rupees (about 25,000 U.S. dollars), out of it, about 1.32 million
rupees (22,000 dollars) has been loaned, said the reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
