<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baht Flotation to Hit Thailand's Property Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The flotation of the baht is
dealing yet another blow to Thailand's ailing property industry,
said the chief of Thailand's largest real estate developer.
</P>
<P>
Anant Assavapokin, managing director of the Land and House,
said the sector would be hit by the end of the year with higher
construction costs pushing up the price of property and turning
away buyers.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's property sector has been in a poor state for about
four years now, with sales of completed office buildings and
apartments being stagnant and developers unable to repay their
loans from banks and interest.
</P>
<P>
The problem now was no one could be sure when the value of the
baht would settle and it was difficult for developers to predict
future capital costs, Anant told a seminar on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said he had ordered all 30 of his sales offices across the
country to stop selling houses currently under, or about to be
constructed, as the company had to recalculate building costs,
which were certain to rise.
</P>
<P>
He said that some people predicted that the baht will go down
to as low as 35 baht per US dollar. If this turned out to be true,
the situation would be even worse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
