<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yuan Hits Record High From Dollar Oversupply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese RMB yuan surged to a
25-month high against the US dollar on the Shanghai-based China
Foreign Exchange Trade Center in June, propelled by an oversupply
of greenbacks in the domestic market, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The renminbi touched an 8.2905 high against the US dollar on
June 25, the highest closing price since May 19, 1995 when it
ended at 8.2892.
</P>
<P>
The yuan continued to rise in June, despite the dollar's strong
performance in the world market. The yuan closed higher at 8.2906
against the dollar on June 27, the last trading day of the month,
up from 8.2914 on June 2.
</P>
<P>
"The growing oversupply of dollars has been a major factor
supporting the yuan's gradual upward trend since the beginning of
the year," a Bank of China dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The dollar supply exceeds demand because of China's strong
trade surplus, steady foreign investment and more foreign
financial institutions doing business in China.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show China posted a 13.9 billion US dollars
trade surplus in the first five months, compared to a 451 million
US dollars deficit the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Relatively tight macro-economic control has curbed inflation,
which caused more support for the yuan. China's benchmark retail
price index rose 0.8 percent in May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Port Cargo Handling Halts due to Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 16 ships were waiting to unload
goods and containers in Chittagong port, the largest seaport in
south Bangladesh, while 17 others were in the outer anchorage till
today, according to port sources.
</P>
<P>
Following a hassle between merchant workers and coaster hatch
workers over cargo handling rights, a massive cargo jam had been
created in the last four days, disrupting import-export trade
through the country's commercial lifeline.
</P>
<P>
Port sources said more than 100 trucks carrying export items,
mainly readymade garments, remained in queue outside the port.
However, port activities, except dispatch and delivery and cargo
handling, are still going on, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 merchant workers stopped handling cargo last
Thursday in protest against engagement of hatch workers in
lighterage cargo from ships anchored at the outer anchorage.
</P>
<P>
Sources said rivalry between the two workers associations, the
Merchant Workers's Union and the Coaster Hatch Workers Union, has
been continuing for a long time over sharing of work at the hatch
of vessels at the outer sea.
</P>
<P>
Kamal Uddin, president of the Merchant Workers' Union", said
"We will continue our strike until and unless the hatch workers
are withdrawn from lighterage works as we are supposed to that
job."
</P>
<P>
The hatch workers, however, said that they were driven out from
their work by the merchant workers by force in 1986 and they were
struggling for the last few years to get back their right of
handling lighterage works at the outer sea.
</P>
<P>
In those days, Chittagong Mayor ABM Mohiuddin Chowdhury and
port authorities were continuing effort to end the dispute between
the two groups, but no sign of development was in sight, said
sources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bangladesh Garments Manufacturers and Exporters
Association (BGMEA) in a statement Saturday urged the government
to immediately deploy the emergency force to break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
The BGMEA's president Golam Quddus apprehended that the
deadlock at Chittagong port would have serious adverse impact on
the country's overall export trade, resulting in colossal loss of
foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign buyers are losing confidence in Bangladesh as the
deadline for export could not be met due to repeated deadlock in
the port," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
