<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Executives Back Baht Float: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The float of the baht since
Wednesday is welcomed by a majority of executives of banks and
finance firms in Thailand, according to the Bangkok Post today
quoting a poll.
</P>
<P>
Of the 131 samples, 85.5 percent agreed with the float, 8.4
percent disagreed and 6.1 percent had no comment.
</P>
<P>
Of the supporters, about 47.7 percent said they supported the
float decision because it reflects the reality prevailing in the
money and capital markets, according to the poll, conducted on
Wednesday and Thursday by the ABAC-KSC Internet Poll Research
Center.
</P>
<P>
About 19.8 percent of the supporters backed the float because
they had confidence in the government's policy to solve economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
The remaining supporters said the float would stimulate capital
flows from abroad (14.4 percent); would yield positive effects on
the economy in the long run (12.6 percent) and would help increase
foreign reserves (5.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
Others said it would cause problems as financial institutions
have not yet been ready for the change (27.3 percent); add debt
burden on leading importers and certain state-owned businesses
(18.2 percent) and cause fluctuations in the value of the baht
(9.0 percent).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
