<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Nurture New-Generation Qualified Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- An agro-forestry training center has
been opened in Pakokku, Myanmar's Magway division, in a bid to
nurture new generation qualified farmers.
</P>
<P>
The training center was set up with financial and technical
assistance from the Organization for Industrial, Spiritual and
Cultural Advancement (OISCA), a Japan-based non-governmental
organization, official paper The New Light of Myanmar reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister for Forestry Chit Swe, at the opening of the
training center Saturday, urged local people to strive for
boosting of crops cultivation and to preserve the environment.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the three objectives, laid down in the
agricultural sector to improve socio-economic development of the
rural people, are being implemented through five reforms namely
land reclamation, water supply, mechanization, application of
quality strains and renovation of technology.
</P>
<P>
He stressed need to employ integrated agricultural system
including agro-forestry cultivation and livestock breeding.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's gross domestic product grew by 5.8 percent in the
1996-97 fiscal year, in which agriculture production went up by
3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's paddy output in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending March
was recorded at nearly 20 million tons with rice export at 271,900
tons, while the paddy output in 1995-96 was at 19 million tons
with 353,100 tons of rice exported, according to official
statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
