<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acceleration of Commercial Integration Process Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Central American commercial
integration process should be accelerated, Carlos Alberto
Federspiel, President of the Federation of Chambers of Commerce of
the Central American isthmus, said here recently.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a recent meeting of representatives of regional
chambers of commerce, Federspiel said "it is important that the
regional economies get ready to work in search of an economic
union, to prepare for the Americas Free Trade Agreement (AFTA)
that must be ratified by 2005."
</P>
<P>
"We are in front of globalization, which is an era of changes
and opportunities," Federspiel told the conference of "The
Chambers of Commerce of the Isthmus and their actions toward AFTA
2005," sponsored by the Chamber of Commerce, Industry, and
Agriculture of Panama (CCIAP).
</P>
<P>
"We have to work fast because those opportunities must be
caught, to try to get together to search for better and bigger
markets," he told the meeting, which was attended by directors of
the chambers of commerce of Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras, and
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Edgardo Carles, President of the
CCIAP, said the Central American countries, together with Panama,
must form an economic bloc to negotiate jointly for a regional
commercial system without trade barriers and customs tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, new progress has been reportedly
achieved in negotiations on regional economic integration in the
Americas. All the countries concerned are to start a new round of
negotiations in Costa Rica in February 1998 on the gradual
realization of a free trade system in the Americas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
