<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Using High-Tech to Improve Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- China has worked out a plan to
establish about 100 urban traffic computer command centers over
the next decade to relieve the increasing traffic jams and
accidents.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that about 280,000 traffic accidents occurred
last year in China, killing 73,655 people and injuring 174,447,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
It is urgent for China to curb traffic congestion and reduce
accidents, as the number of motor vehicles has been quickly
expanding in the bicycle capital of the world, according to
Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
Large and medium cities will install electronic
video-monitoring systems to direct its traffic flows, said Zhang
Dianping, chief of the Traffic Management Bureau under the
Ministry of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
The plan will also raise speed limits 10 to 15 percent in
densely populated areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The traffic-monitoring systems consist of programmed signal
light control system, cable supervision system, transport
information exchange system, traffic broadcasting system,
satellite global positioning system and wired and wireless
communications systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Continues Minsheng Discussions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Discussions continue about the
World Bank's proposed participation in China Minsheng Banking
Corp, today's China Daily quoted a top Minsheng official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Minsheng is China's only non-State bank.
</P>
<P>
Minsheng Chairman Jing Shuping said the bank had given its
financial statements to the International Finance Corp (IFC), a
World Bank subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
More talks are expected after the company finishes studying the
statements. IFC, which specializes in financing the private
sector, last year asked to buy a stake in Minsheng, which
responded warmly.
</P>
<P>
China's financial authorities supported the idea, Jing
said. The purchase would be the second case of international
involvement in China's banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The first was the Asian Development Bank's equity investment in
China Everbright Bank last year.
</P>
<P>
The issue drew international banking attention because the
country's banking sector had excluded foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC) said ADB's purchase was not
"foreign" because ADB was an international institution, of which
China holds a share.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank said the Everbright case would be an
experiment.
</P>
<P>
Jing said Minsheng hoped to receive IFC assistance in its
efforts to become a world standard commercial bank. That has been
one of the bank's top tasks since the bank opened early last year.
</P>
<P>
The All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce (ACFIC)
launched the bank to serve the country's capital-starved private
sector. Jing is chairman of the federation.
</P>
<P>
The bank's majority shareholders are private enterprises. It
aroused IFC's interest, which had been waiting to play a role in
the country's financial reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0122 </DOCNO>
