<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Cultural News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are news about
recent culture, arts, and entertainment related events occurred in
the last few days:
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican Congress and the state Autonomous
Metropolitan University (UAM) designed a data base that contains
cultural, scientific, educational, and technical agreements signed
with other countries.
</P>
<P>
The data bank contains some 700 agreements on cultural
legislative matters signed by Mexico with other countries since
1903, and also includes declarations on historical monuments,
museums, and archeological zones.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The show "The One-Thousand-and-One Evitas"
about the life of the late Eva Peron is being held from June to
July in Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
Eva Duarte de Peron (1919-1952), known as Evita, was wife of
the late president Juan Domingo Peron and has a big popularity
with the Argentine people.
</P>
<P>
The exhibit shows photographs, dresses, and film clips of her
wedding with President Peron and the former first lady's social
life.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Plan Real for the economic stabilization of
Brazil was fundamental for the cultural development of the
country, Brazilian Culture Minister Francisco Weffort said today.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government has given allotted 215 million dollars
to culture in 1996, surpassing the 105 million dollars assigned in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The budget for culture will be 250 million dollars this year,
as announced by the Education authorities.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- A contest of children's stories written by
children 7 to 13 years old who are in the primary school in any of
the four Mercosur countries is open from now until August 17.
</P>
<P>
The stories must have as a subject matter the home, the
parents, brothers and sisters, relatives, and some events.
</P>
<P>
The prizes, of three categories, will be awarded September 1 of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The contest, organized by the "Destino" magazine of Punta del
Este, Uruguay, has a jury made up of well-known writers from
Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, and Paraguay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
