<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 26 People Killed in Road Accident in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif have expressed profound
grief and sorrow over the tragic bus accident occurred on Saturday
in the north of the country killing 26 passengers.
</P>
<P>
The twenty-six passengers, most of them soldiers, were killed
when the bus fell into a ravine on its way from the northern city
of Gilgit to Rawalpindi, a twin city of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that the exact cause of the accident has
not been known so far but it is feared that the brake of the bus
might had failed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministry Issues Alert Against Cotton Pests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese agrotechnicians are being
urged to improve their monitoring of bollworms infesting cotton
fields and take stringent and effective measures against the pest
inflicting a disaster, according to the China Information Daily.
</P>
<P>
China this year has more than 4.565 million hectares of
cotton, slightly less than that for 1996, but the newspaper
reported that a bollworm disaster once again threatened to infest
the crop as it came to the blossom stage.
</P>
<P>
Bai Zhijian, Vice Minister of Agriculture, said at a national
cotton meeting that the fight against bollworms is important to
keep cotton output on a par with that of last year.
</P>
<P>
To do so, he said, growers need to raise their yields since the
total acreage under cotton is less than last year's.
</P>
<P>
Bollworms brought disasters in cotton fields of the Yellow and
Huaihe river valleys in 1992, causing an economic loss of four
billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970706.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collins Retains WBO Super-middleweight Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Irishman Steve Collins retained his
World Boxing Organisation super-middleweight title by stopping
American challenger Craig Cummings in the third round at Glasgow
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was the 32-year-old Dubliner's seventh successful defence of
the title he took off British boxer Chris Eubank in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Kilt-wearing Collins was left on his backside by a Cummings
left hook after just 16 seconds but quickly reasserted himself by
decking the American, a late replacement for Syrian-born Anwar
Oshana, before the end of a pulsating opening round.
</P>
<P>
It was all one way in the second, with 29-year-old Cummings
unable to cope with the power of his Irish opponent.
</P>
<P>
And it was no surprise when a series of heavy punches without
reply prompted the referee to call off the fight after one minutes
17 seconds of the third round.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Collins now improved his record to 36 wins,
20 knockouts and three defeats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
